&gt; Kent Beck wrote:
&gt; &gt; @Test takes two optional parameters. A test annotated 
&gt; @Test(timeout=100)
&gt; &gt; will fail if the test takes longer than 100 milliseconds to 
&gt; complete. A test
&gt; &gt; annotated @Test(expected=NullPointerException.class) will fail if a
&gt; &gt; NullPointerException is not thrown and succeed if a 
&gt; NullPointerException is
&gt; &gt; thrown.
&gt; 
&gt; Kent,
&gt; 
&gt; These are both examples of decorators (as I&#39;m sure you know).
&gt; 
&gt; Rather than simply hard-code in just two decorators, is there 
&gt; any chance 
&gt; you could provide a generic parameter for defining decorators 
&gt; on a per test 
&gt; method (and class) basis?
&gt; 
&gt; e.g.
&gt; @TestSuite(decorator=foo.bar.WibbleDecorator.class)
&gt; public class SomeTest {
&gt; 
&gt;    @Test(decorator=foo.bar.XyzzyDecorator.class)
&gt;    public void testWhatever() {
&gt;      ...
&gt;    }
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; The decorator support in JUnit is a very powerful technique, 
&gt; and one that&#39;s 
&gt; been underutilised by many JUnit extensions. One reason is 
&gt; that decorating 
&gt; tests isn&#39;t that easy - while suite-level decorators aren&#39;t hard, 
&gt; testcase-level decorators require populating the suite by hand. :( 
&gt; Annotation-based decorator declaration would go a long way to 
&gt; solving that.
&gt; 
&gt; I&#39;d also like to see an annotation-based version of the 
&gt; suite() method, 
&gt; thus keeping in the trend of providing alternatives to the existing 
&gt; reflection based techniques.
&gt; 
&gt; Robert.
